A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
Firstly, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly inappropriate system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, facing the inefficacy of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of intense effort.
The English translation of the given French sentence is:  "This is why it is essential that this year there be undertaken a truly proactive approach at both European and global levels."
In September next year, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a strong global protection system for the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let's hope that the states will be ready to engage in a concrete and lasting manner.
This necessary commitment sadly failed to materialize during the year 2015.
Indeed, the international community would have been able to mitigate the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even minimal support to the countries on the front line – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which collectively host no fewer than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better equipped to house, feed, and educate refugees, thereby reducing the temptation for them to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone as much as 21 billion euros annually in the coming years.
But the financial implications of the crisis are disproportionate to its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, only to endure a exhausting journey through the Balkans thereafter.
Close to 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, with many European countries turning their backs on the survivors by refusing to give them refuge.
The most cynical political actors mercilessly exploited citizens' fears by promoting a hateful nationalist vision, either by ignoring or distorting the migrant experience.
For example, in the United States, not one of the 780,000 refugees installed since September 11, 2001, has been guilty of terrorist acts.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with gaining political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support within formerly liberal strongholds as well.
The anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also prompts traditional parties to promote a hostile immigration policy as well.
This situation has considerably damaged European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million of refugees who arrived on its shores only managed to "relocate" 190 of them.
The border controls of six Schengen space countries have been reinstated, at least temporarily.
To the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today to be nationalist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis is not limited to Europe alone; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Regardless, the EU likely faces today a threat to its very existence, which it will be able to overcome only by demonstrating firmly the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
This is why it falls to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and safe routes allowing refugees to reach Europe.
It does not mean that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
However, it remains for the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to welcome, and to use orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
Such a system would allow for protecting migrants while safeguarding Europe (thanks to the ability to fully examine requests).
Beyond a approach aimed at discouraging asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would also allow projecting an image of solidarity towards the frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
An equally important aspect of this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to these efforts.
This leads us to the second priority for 2016: building a strong global system for protecting vulnerable refugee and migrant populations.
This objective will primarily require that more countries agree to accept refugees.
In recent years, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has only been able to resettle fewer than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Several million of them end up in a situation of prolonged migration, with an estimated average duration of 25 years, trapped in some sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a possible return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary for developed countries to commit to hosting an annual cumulative number close to one million refugees, either through their resettlement or by granting them a humanitarian, student, professional, or other visa.
Canada having declared that it would welcome 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will need to support the integration of refugees in important host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current state of affairs, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually required for each refugee for housing, food, healthcare, education, and vocational training during the early years of resettlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of constructing or upgrading infrastructure.
For example, in Lebanon, the water supply systems suffer from the pressure exerted by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if countries in Europe and elsewhere rid themselves of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these are still seen as a burden, or even a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and transforming fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if the host states manage to integrate the migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through financial inflows).
Last month, in Paris, the international community demonstrated that it is capable of prioritizing a broader global goal over national interests: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary that a similar effort be directed towards building a better protection system for migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – and a profound testing of the civil health of democratic societies around the world.
